    "summary": "The Egyptian Revolution of 1952 was a military coup on July 23, 1952, carried out by a group of army officers known as the Free Officers Movement, led by General Muhammad Naguib and the charismatic Colonel Gamal Abdel Nasser. The revolution overthrew King Farouk I, ending Egypt's constitutional monarchy and the political influence of the British-backed aristocracy. Farouk abdicated and went into exile within days.\n\nThe Free Officers were motivated by Egypt's defeat in the 1948 Arab-Israeli War, which they blamed on corrupt political leadership and continued British dominance of Egyptian affairs. They also resented the semi-colonial status Egypt retained despite nominal independence. The revolution abolished the monarchy in 1953, declared Egypt a republic, and progressively dismantled the political parties associated with the old regime. Naguib became president, but Nasser outmaneuvered him and became the dominant figure by 1954.\n\nUnder Nasser, Egypt nationalized the Suez Canal in 1956, precipitating the [[event:2672|Suez Crisis]], and became a leading voice of Arab nationalism and anti-colonialism. The Egyptian Revolution inspired similar military-nationalist movements across the Arab world, transforming the political landscape of the Middle East and North Africa throughout the 1950s and 1960s. Nasser's model of secular Arab nationalism became one of the defining political forces of the post-colonial world.",
